  {
    "client_msg_id": "4dc5644a-8962-4cf1-b54d-5079dd046d2d",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Haha, sorry, I used those \"scare quotes\" a bit vaguely. My project is taking the Clojure approach, where you design a new language to sit atop another _host language_, and make some aspects of the host available in your language. The project (a visual PL) is designed to let you create layered visual DSLs, and it'll run atop various JS contexts (Electron &amp; browser), so I am feeling some tension around the question of... what should be in the core runtime that sits directly atop JS, versus what should be implemented in the first visual DSL level? Sort of like the questions that come up when bootstrapping: what minimal primitives do you need/want in order to go metacircular and start compiling your own compiler and/or implementing things in terms of themselves? I haven't found much in the way of good discussion about this matter, outside the realm of Lisp. I wasn't aware that VPRI had tackled the subject, and I haven't seen that paper about Open, Extensible Object Models, so this should help me explore the topic and crystallize my thinking.",
